Caption: For the last couple of years, the easiest GEO hack in the book was to publish a "best [category]" listicle and rank yourself #1. It worked to influence AI answers, and in many cases, it still does.
But it also might be handing the win to your competitors now, at least on AI Overviews.
I pulled 100 B2B "best [category]" queries from Google's AI Overviews across three dates between April and June, and separated two of the main AI search success metrics: getting cited as a source vs. actually getting recommended in the answer. Turns out those are very different outcomes.
When a brand's own self-promotional listicle got cited, that brand was left out of the actual recommendation 69% of the time. And the recommendations went to the established competitors they'd listed in their own article. 
So you write a listicle, name your competitors, call yourself the best, and Google cites you as the source (citation) while recommending everyone else on your list. So basically, you just inadvertently made the case for your competition.
Google seems to have decoupled what it cites from who it recommends, and the recommendations appears to be anchored to actual authority (who the rest of the web talks about and links to) rather than how many times you've called yourself #1. If you're a massive, well-known brand you can still get away with it. If you're not, you might be voting against yourself.
This isn't happening in a vacuum either. Google demoted a lot of these sites in organic search back in January, the drops got worse during the May core update, and AI Overviews have started adding disclaimers on AI Overviews warning that a category is "saturated with self-proclaimed experts." (Claude does the same thing, for what it's worth.)
If AI citations are your main KPI, I'd reconsider. I’d argue that being recommended is much more valuable.
